description:
Goal: Create TypeScript interfaces for domain model

Why:
- Types-first approach catches design issues early
- Shared vocabulary between detector, analyzers, reporter
- Enables type-safe composition of analysis pipeline

How we arrived here:
- LeakScope's differentiator is "blast radius" - what a leaked secret can access
- Need to model: detected secret ‚Üí analysis ‚Üí blast radius ‚Üí report
- Each cloud provider has different "permissions" concept (IAM policies, PAT scopes, API keys)

Types needed:
```typescript
interface DetectedSecret {
  type: 'aws_access_key' | 'github_pat' | 'stripe_key' | ...;
  value: string;  // masked in output
  location: { file: string; line: number };
}

interface BlastRadius {
  provider: string;
  permissions: string[];      // what it CAN do
  resources: string[];        // what it can ACCESS
  severity: 'critical' | 'high' | 'medium' | 'low';
}

interface AnalysisResult {
  secret: DetectedSecret;
  blastRadius: BlastRadius;
  wasUsed: boolean;           // audit log check (future)
  recommendations: string[];  // rotation steps
}
```

TDD: Test that types compile and example objects pass type checking

Done when:
- src/types.ts exists with all interfaces
- Example objects in tests/types.test.ts compile
- No any types except where unavoidable

Goal: Determine what AWS resources a leaked key can access

Why:
- AWS is #1 leaked cloud credential type
- IAM SimulatePrincipalPolicy is official AWS API for permission checking
- Actual permissions often differ from expected (policy drift, wildcards)

How we arrived here:
- Evoidea refinement identified "blast radius" as key differentiator
- Other tools detect leaks but don't answer "how bad is this?"
- AWS IAM API provides authoritative answer without guessing

Implementation:
```typescript
async function analyzeAwsKey(accessKey: string, secretKey: string): Promise<BlastRadius> {
  const iam = new IAMClient({ credentials: { accessKeyId, secretAccessKey }});

  // Check common dangerous actions
  const actions = [
    's3:*', 'iam:*', 'ec2:*', 'lambda:*', 
    'secretsmanager:GetSecretValue', 'ssm:GetParameter'
  ];

  const results = await iam.send(new SimulatePrincipalPolicyCommand({
    PolicySourceArn: await getCallerArn(),
    ActionNames: actions,
  }));

  return {
    provider: 'aws',
    permissions: results.EvaluationResults.filter(r => r.EvalDecision === 'allowed').map(r => r.EvalActionName),
    resources: await listAccessibleResources(iam),
    severity: calculateSeverity(permissions),
  };
}
```

TDD:
- Mock IAM responses for different permission levels
- Test severity calculation: admin=critical, s3-only=medium, readonly=low
- Test error handling when key is invalid/revoked

Done when:
- src/analyzers/aws.ts exports analyzeAwsKey()
- Returns BlastRadius with actual permissions
- Handles expired/invalid keys gracefully

Goal: Create registry pattern for adding new cloud providers

Why:
- MVP has 3 providers, will grow to 10+
- Each provider has different API, auth, permission model
- Registry pattern enables clean extension without modifying core

How we arrived here:
- Evoidea evolution showed "multi-scanner hub" as viable direction
- Registry pattern is standard for plugin architectures
- Keeps core simple, providers isolated

Implementation:
```typescript
interface Analyzer {
  name: string;
  secretTypes: SecretType[];  // which secrets this analyzer handles
  analyze(secret: DetectedSecret): Promise<BlastRadius>;
}

class AnalyzerRegistry {
  private analyzers = new Map<SecretType, Analyzer>();

  register(analyzer: Analyzer): void {
    for (const type of analyzer.secretTypes) {
      this.analyzers.set(type, analyzer);
    }
  }

  async analyze(secret: DetectedSecret): Promise<AnalysisResult> {
    const analyzer = this.analyzers.get(secret.type);
    if (!analyzer) return { secret, blastRadius: null, recommendations: ['Unknown secret type'] };
    return { secret, blastRadius: await analyzer.analyze(secret), recommendations: [] };
  }
}

// Usage
const registry = new AnalyzerRegistry();
registry.register(new AwsAnalyzer());
registry.register(new GitHubAnalyzer());
registry.register(new StripeAnalyzer());
```

TDD:
- Test registration of multiple analyzers
- Test correct analyzer dispatching by secret type
- Test fallback for unknown secret types

Done when:
- src/analyzers/registry.ts exports AnalyzerRegistry
- AWS and GitHub analyzers registered
- Unknown secrets handled gracefully

Goal: Determine what GitHub resources a leaked PAT can access

Why:
- GitHub PATs are second most common leaked credential
- Scopes vary widely: read-only vs admin vs workflow
- Users often don't know what scopes their PAT has

How we arrived here:
- Evoidea identified GitHub as critical provider alongside AWS
- GitHub fine-grained PATs have complex permission model
- Classic PATs have simpler scopes but still need analysis

Implementation:
```typescript
async function analyzeGitHubPat(token: string): Promise<BlastRadius> {
  const octokit = new Octokit({ auth: token });

  // Check token scopes via API response headers
  const { headers } = await octokit.rest.users.getAuthenticated();
  const scopes = headers['x-oauth-scopes']?.split(', ') || [];

  // Map scopes to permissions
  const permissions = scopes.flatMap(scope => SCOPE_PERMISSIONS[scope]);

  // Check accessible repos
  const repos = await octokit.paginate(octokit.rest.repos.listForAuthenticatedUser);

  return {
    provider: 'github',
    permissions,
    resources: repos.map(r => r.full_name),
    severity: calculateGitHubSeverity(scopes),
  };
}
```

Severity mapping:
- critical: admin:org, delete_repo, workflow
- high: repo (full access), admin:repo_hook
- medium: public_repo, read:org
- low: read:user, user:email

TDD:
- Mock Octokit responses for different scope combinations
- Test severity calculation for each scope level
- Test handling of expired/revoked tokens

Done when:
- src/analyzers/github.ts exports analyzeGitHubPat()
- Returns BlastRadius with scopes and accessible repos
- Handles invalid tokens gracefully

Goal: Create main entry point that orchestrates the analysis pipeline

Why:
- GitHub Actions need single entry point (index.ts ‚Üí dist/index.js)
- Pipeline: detect secrets ‚Üí analyze each ‚Üí report to PR
- Error handling at top level for graceful failures

How we arrived here:
- Standard GitHub Action pattern: @actions/core for inputs/outputs
- @actions/github for PR comment API
- Pipeline composition from previous tasks

Implementation:
```typescript
import * as core from '@actions/core';
import * as github from '@actions/github';
import { detectSecrets } from './detector';
import { AnalyzerRegistry } from './analyzers/registry';
import { generateComment } from './reporter';

async function run(): Promise<void> {
  try {
    // Get changed files from PR
    const token = core.getInput('github-token', { required: true });
    const octokit = github.getOctokit(token);
    const { pull_request } = github.context.payload;

    // Detect secrets in changed files
    const files = await getChangedFiles(octokit, pull_request);
    const secrets = files.flatMap(f => detectSecrets(f.content, f.path));

    if (secrets.length === 0) {
      core.info('No secrets detected');
      return;
    }

    // Analyze each secret
    const registry = createRegistry();
    const results = await Promise.all(secrets.map(s => registry.analyze(s)));

    // Post comment
    const comment = generateComment(results);
    await postComment(octokit, pull_request, comment);

    // Fail if critical severity
    if (results.some(r => r.blastRadius?.severity === 'critical')) {
      core.setFailed('Critical severity secrets detected');
    }
  } catch (error) {
    core.setFailed(error.message);
  }
}

run();
```

TDD:
- Test pipeline with mock inputs
- Test critical severity fails the action
- Test no-secrets case exits cleanly

Done when:
- src/index.ts exports working action
- Pipeline connects all components
- Errors are caught and reported via core.setFailed
